@merlimat @msb-at-yahoo @saandrews  - curl works with asio (example below) but getting it work with boost::asio 1.41 was a bit difficult since few methods are not supported in the old version and also in the standup there was an issue of not liking libcurl so I abandoned the effort.

Anyways, I will spend some more time on this and try to get the old asio to work with libcurl.

https://curl.haxx.se/libcurl/c/asiohiper.html

@merlimat Thank you for your detailed explanation. It's a sad story that my lab only have machines with HDDs. So now I have to test the performance of Pulsar on HDDs. And I will suggest my advisor to buy some SSDs to present the real power of Pulsar. 

Attached is my bookie-stats file generated by one of the bookies during the test. Hope it can help to reflect what is the bottleneck of the bookie.
[bookie-stats.zip](https://github.com/yahoo/pulsar/files/884610/bookie-stats.zip)

@sschepens The `NoLedger` state is the normal state after the cursor has been recovered, and before any new mark-delete has been issued.

The idea there is to defer the ZK writes for creating a new ledger and updating the cursor z-node until is needed.

In the log that you posted before, can you give the topic/subscription name for which you have added the internal stats?

@merlimat the subscription is `8caa83e304674002a34f441f34f73f63-shipping-feed-orders` and the topic is `persistent://fury/global/cbead41f2a5849b5a5be64df0f3521d2-orders-orders/cbead41f2a5849b5a5be64df0f3521d2-orders-orders`, the information provided is specifically for partition 0 (`persistent://fury/global/cbead41f2a5849b5a5be64df0f3521d2-orders-orders/cbead41f2a5849b5a5be64df0f3521d2-orders-orders-partition-0`).

> @sschepens The NoLedger state is the normal state after the cursor has been recovered, and before any new mark-delete has been issued.

I understand that and I have read the code, but the state is still NoLedger and it has not changed, by the stats-internal it was last changed 11 days ago.

@merlimat probably `partition-0` was not affected when I restarted those brokers, which is why the issue is currently present in it, I will check the stats for `partition-2`

> Any hints in logs why the TTL is failing to be enforced?

The logs are being printend and there doesn't seem to be any failures, it just seems that in that period of time i took the logs there weren't any from PersistentMessageExpiryMonitor.

@merlimat - I was running tests on the old tag 17.1 hence faced this issue, I don't see the issue anymore after upgrade to 17.2 - The fix must be one of the many things fixed in loadManager.
Do you want me to close the PR or does the check seem reasonable on its own?

@saandrews - We return an error if we get an exception in fetching the loadReport from zk, but if the loadReport has null params then we just return that. Also the proto file suggests the same:

```
        optional string brokerServiceUrl      = 1; // Optional in case of error
	optional string brokerServiceUrlTls   = 2;
```

Found the issue - it was a bug in testing 
I was hitting the broker before the Pulsar Service had started - closing the PR as this will never happen in production since we register on the vip only after the service has started

@rdhabalia - thanks for the help
